{"cursor":"17604","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox language |name=Bouyei |nativename=Haausqyaix |altname=Giay (Yay)\n|states=China (Guizhou, Yunnan, and Sichuan Provinces) Vietnam |speakers=\n2,650,000 |date=2000 |ethnicity=Bouyei, Giay |familycolor=TaiâKadai |fam2=Tai\n|fam3=Northern |script=Latin, Sawndip |iso3=pcc |notice=IPA }}\n\nThe 'Bouyei language' (autonym: 'Haausqyaix' also spelled Buyi, Buyei, or\nPuyi; [http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=pcc\nEthnologue.com] , or {{lang|vi|tiáº¿ng GiÃ¡y}}), is a language spoken by the\nBouyei ethnic group [http://www.travel-china.net/buyi-nationality.html Travel-\nchina.net] of southern Guizhou Province in mainland China. Classified as a\nmember of the Northern Tai group in the Tai languages branch of the TaiâKadai\nlanguage family, the language has over 2.5 million native speakers and is also\nused by the Giay people () in some parts of Vietnam. There are native speakers\nliving in France or the United States as well, which immigrated from China or\nVietnam. About 98% of the native speakers are in China.\n\nBouyei's characteristics are similar to the other members of its language\nbranch. It is generally monosyllabic, and word order and particles are the main\nforms of grammar. Bouyei's syllable initials match up closely to the other\nNorthern Tai languages, with relatively fast simplification and merging. Bouyei\nsentences can be shown to contain many different levels of phrasing.\n\nThe contemporary Bouyei script was developed after the abandonment of the Bouyei-\nZhuang Script Alliance Policy in 1981, and was designed from 1981 to 1985. It is\nfocused and phonologically representative, and takes the Wangmo County dialect\nas its foundation.\n","linknr":328,"url":"Bouyei_language","recorded":1374860171,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Bouyei_language&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Bouyei_language&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc